---
Title: Anchors
---

# Anchors

An *anchor* is a named landmark you drop into the middle of your prose so that
you — or a reader, or another part of the document — can link straight to that
spot. HTML has long supported this through the `id` attribute and same-page links
of the form `#name`, but plain Markdown gives you no convenient way to place an
`id` on an arbitrary point in a paragraph. JMarkdown closes that gap with a tiny,
single-purpose piece of inline syntax: the anchor symbol.

When you write the unicode anchor emoji immediately followed by a name, JMarkdown
emits an empty `<span>` whose `id` is that name. The span has no visible content
and no styling of its own, so it never disturbs the surrounding text — it simply
marks a position you can jump to.

## The syntax

An anchor is the anchor emoji (⚓️, unicode U+2693 followed by the variation
selector U+FE0F) followed immediately, with no space, by a name:

```
⚓️name
```

The name may contain letters, digits, hyphens, and underscores
(`[a-zA-Z0-9_-]`). Matching stops at the first character outside that set, so the
anchor ends cleanly where the name ends and ordinary prose resumes — you do not
need a delimiter or a trailing space to close it. The example below places an
anchor and then, a little later, links back to it. Notice that the anchor itself
produces nothing you can see; only the link is visible:

:::markdown-demo
Here is a paragraph with an ⚓️landmark planted inside
it. The anchor is invisible, but it gives us a target.

Much later, somewhere else on the page, we can [jump to that
landmark](#landmark).
:::

An anchor may sit anywhere a span of inline text may appear — at the start of a
line, mid-sentence, or at the very end. Because the tokenizer is an inline
extension, it does not need a line of its own:

:::markdown-demo
A definition can begin ⚓️def-utility right where the
term is introduced, so a cross-reference lands the
reader on the exact sentence rather than the top of a
section.

See the [definition of utility](#def-utility) above.
:::

## How an anchor renders

The renderer is deliberately minimal. The anchor

```
⚓️introduction
```

becomes exactly

```html
<span id="introduction"></span>
```

That is the whole of it: an empty element carrying the `id`. There is no class,
no inline style, and no text content, so anchors add nothing to the visual flow
of the document and cannot accidentally introduce a stray blank line or a gap.
You attach the meaning — anchors are purely a target for links.

### Linking to an anchor

Once an anchor exists, you reach it with an ordinary same-page Markdown link
whose destination is `#` followed by the anchor's name:

```markdown
You planted the anchor with ⚓️results, and you reach it
with [a link to the results](#results).
```

Same-page links are a standard browser feature, so this needs nothing special
from JMarkdown beyond the anchor itself. Clicking the link scrolls the page to
the anchored span; the URL gains a `#results` fragment, which means the position
is also shareable and bookmarkable.

## Choosing good anchor names

Because the `id` you write becomes a fragment in the page's URL and an HTML `id`,
a couple of small disciplines pay off:

- **Keep names unique within a page.** Two elements with the same `id` are
  invalid HTML, and a `#name` link will jump to whichever the browser finds
  first. If you anchor `intro` twice, only one of them is reliably reachable.
- **Prefer readable, hyphenated names.** `proof-of-lemma-3` is kinder in a URL
  than `pol3`, and it survives editing better.
- **Mind the allowed characters.** Only letters, digits, hyphens, and
  underscores are part of the name; the anchor stops at anything else. So
  `⚓️section.2` anchors `section` and leaves `.2` as ordinary text — use
  `⚓️section-2` instead.

## Anchors and the `{#id}` directive

JMarkdown offers a second, related way to create a link target, and it helps to
know when each is the right tool. The inline attribute directive
(documented under [Syntax Adjustments](syntax-adjustments.html)) attaches an
`id` — and optionally classes — to the *element that contains it*:

:::markdown-demo
1. This list item is given an id of its own {#first-step}
2. A second item, with classes attached {.note}
3. A third, ordinary item.
:::

The two features are complementary, not redundant:

| | anchor (`⚓️name`) | attribute directive (`{#name}`) |
|---|---|---|
| What it targets | a fresh empty `<span>` at the exact spot you write it | the enclosing block element (list item, paragraph, heading, …) |
| Leaves a visible element? | yes — an empty span, but it is invisible | no — the marker span is removed in post-processing |
| Can it add classes? | no | yes (`{.class #id}`) |
| Best when | you want to point at a precise position inside running prose | you want to label and style a whole block |

Reach for an anchor when the target is a *point* — a particular sentence, a term
as it is first defined, the line a footnote refers back to. Reach for the
attribute directive when the target is a *block* you also want to address as a
unit (and perhaps style).

Headings are a third case worth remembering: JMarkdown already gives every
heading an automatic `id` derived from its text, so you can usually link to a
section with `#the-heading-text` without placing any anchor at all. Anchors are
for the places automatic ids do not reach.

## Output formats

Anchors are an HTML-oriented feature. The renderer emits the same empty `<span>`
in every output format, so in LaTeX output the literal span markup is passed
through rather than translated into a `\label`. If you are authoring for print as
well as the web and need a print cross-reference target, place an explicit
`\label{…}` in a LaTeX-only context (for example with the `:TeX[…]` inline
directive or a `:::TeX` block) alongside the anchor, and use the anchor for the
HTML side.

## Reference

| Item | Value |
|---|---|
| Syntax | `⚓️name` (anchor emoji, then the name, no space) |
| Anchor emoji | ⚓️ — unicode U+2693 (ANCHOR) + U+FE0F (variation selector) |
| Allowed name characters | letters, digits, `-`, `_` (`[a-zA-Z0-9_-]+`) |
| Level | inline — may appear anywhere inline text is allowed |
| HTML output | `<span id="name"></span>` |
| How to link to it | a same-page Markdown link to `#name` |
| Registered on | both parsers (the main `marked` instance and `marked_copy`) |

